  "prompt": "My single mom has been horrible to me, how do I make her Los me I am 14 year olds, I need help?",
  "response": "I understand you're going through a difficult time with your mom, and it's tough when you feel like the person who should be your biggest supporter is causing you pain. At 14, you're in a really challenging stage of life, and having a strained relationship with your mom can make things even harder.\n\nIt sounds like you're looking for ways to distance yourself from her, but I want to gently suggest that might not be the best long-term solution. Instead of trying to make her \"lose\" you, perhaps we can explore ways to improve the situation or find healthy ways for you to cope.\n\nHere are a few things you could consider:\n\n*   **Talk to a trusted adult:** Is there a relative, teacher, counselor, or friend's parent you feel comfortable talking to? Sharing your feelings with someone who can offer support and guidance can make a big difference.\n*   **Focus on what you can control:** You can't control your mom's behavior, but you can control how you react to it. Try to find healthy ways to manage your emotions, like exercising, writing in a journal, or listening to music.\n*   **Communicate your feelings:** When you're calm, try talking to your mom about how her actions affect you. Use \"I\" statements to express your feelings without blaming her (e.g., \"I feel hurt when you say...\").\n*   **Seek professional help:** A therapist or counselor can provide you with tools and strategies for navigating your relationship with your mom and managing your emotions.\n*   **Set boundaries:** It's okay to set boundaries with your mom to protect your emotional well-being. This could mean limiting your interactions with her or refusing to engage in arguments.\n\nIf you are in immediate danger or feel unsafe, please reach out for help immediately. You can call 911 or a local emergency number. You can also call the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 800-799-SAFE (7233) or the Childhelp USA hotline at 800-422-4453.\n\nI know this is a lot to take in, but please remember that you're not alone and there are people who care about you and want to help. Take things one step at a time, and don't be afraid to ask for support when you need it.",
